<p><b>Just War</b> theory is a <a href="/wiki/Doctrine" title="Doctrine">doctrine</a> of military ethics of <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Rome" title="Ancient Rome">Roman</a> philosophical and <a href="/wiki/Catholicism" title="Catholicism">Catholic</a> origin<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> studied by moral <a href="/wiki/Theologian" title="Theologian" class="mw-redirect">theologians</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ethicist" title="Ethicist">ethicists</a> and international <a href="/wiki/Policy_maker" title="Policy maker" class="mw-redirect">policy makers</a> which holds that a <a href="/wiki/Conflict" title="Conflict">conflict</a> can and ought to meet the criteria of <a href="/wiki/Philosophy" title="Philosophy">philosophical</a>, <a href="/wiki/Religion" title="Religion">religious</a> or <a href="/wiki/Politics" title="Politics">political</a> <a href="/wiki/Justice" title="Justice">justice</a>, provided it follows certain <a href="/wiki/Indicative_conditional" title="Indicative conditional">conditions</a>.</p>
