<p><a name="References" id="References"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Just_War&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: References">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">References</span></h2>
<div class="references-small">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-0"><b><a href="#cite_ref-0" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/war/" class="external free" title="http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/war/" rel="nofollow">http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/war/</a> The first philosophers of just war were <a href="/wiki/Aristotle" title="Aristotle">Aristotle</a> and <a href="/wiki/Cicero" title="Cicero">Cicero</a>, and the first theologians <a href="/wiki/Augustine_of_Hippo" title="Augustine of Hippo">St. Augustine</a> and <a href="/wiki/St._Thomas_Aquinas" title="St. Thomas Aquinas" class="mw-redirect">St. Thomas Aquinas</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.iep.utm.edu/j/justwar.htm" class="external free" title="http://www.iep.utm.edu/j/justwar.htm" rel="nofollow">http://www.iep.utm.edu/j/justwar.htm</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/ethics/war/just/introduction.shtml" class="external text" title="http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/ethics/war/just/introduction.shtml" rel="nofollow">BBC - Religion &amp; Ethics - Just War Theory - introduction</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://olympia.anglican.org/churches/B/stdunstan/Beliefs/Christians_War/Christians_War_2.htm" class="external text" title="http://olympia.anglican.org/churches/B/stdunstan/Beliefs/Christians_War/Christians_War_2.htm" rel="nofollow">Christians and War: Augustine of Hippo and the "Just War Theory"</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-4"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://olympia.anglican.org/churches/B/stdunstan/Beliefs/Christians_War/Christians_War_3.htm" class="external text" title="http://olympia.anglican.org/churches/B/stdunstan/Beliefs/Christians_War/Christians_War_3.htm" rel="nofollow">Christians and War: Thomas Aquinas refines the "Just War" Theory</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-5"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.justwartheory.com" class="external text" title="http://www.justwartheory.com" rel="nofollow">JustWarTheory.com</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-6"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.eppc.org/publications/pubID.1998/pub_detail.asp" class="external text" title="http://www.eppc.org/publications/pubID.1998/pub_detail.asp" rel="nofollow">Home &gt; Publications &gt;</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-Childress-7"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Childress_7-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREF.5B.5BJames_Childress.7CChildress.2C_James_F..5D.5D1978"><a href="/wiki/James_Childress" title="James Childress">Childress, James F.</a> (1978). "Just-War Theories: The Bases, Interrelations, Priorities, and Functions of Their Criteria". <i>Theological Studies</i> <b>39</b>: 427–45.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Just-War+Theories%3A+The+Bases%2C+Interrelations%2C+Priorities%2C+and+Functions+of+Their+Criteria&amp;rft.jtitle=Theological+Studies&amp;rft.aulast=%5B%5BJames+Childress%7CChildress%2C+James+F.%5D%5D&amp;rft.au=%5B%5BJames+Childress%7CChildress%2C+James+F.%5D%5D&amp;rft.date=1978&amp;rft.volume=39&amp;rft.pages=427%E2%80%9345&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Just_War"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m2065/is_n2_v48/ai_18310385/print?tag=artBody;col1" class="external text" title="http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m2065/is_n2_v48/ai_18310385/print?tag=artBody;col1" rel="nofollow">Sharp, Gene</a>, "Beyond just war and pacifism: nonviolent struggle toward justice, freedom and peace" Ecumenical Review, April, 1996.</li>
<li id="cite_note-9"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,80875,00.html" class="external free" title="http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,80875,00.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,80875,00.html</a></li>
</ol>
</div>
<p><a name="Further_reading" id="Further_reading"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Just_War&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Further reading">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Further reading</span></h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Max_Heindel" title="Max Heindel">Heindel, Max</a>, <i>The Rosicrucian Philosophy in Questions and Answers - Volume II</i> (<a href="http://www.rosicrucian.com/2qa/2qaeng09.htm#question163" class="external text" title="http://www.rosicrucian.com/2qa/2qaeng09.htm#question163" rel="nofollow">The Philosophy of War</a>, <i>World War I reference</i>, ed. 1918), <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0911274901" class="internal">ISBN 0-911274-90-1</a> (Describing a philosophy of war and just war concepts from a <a href="/wiki/Rosicrucian" title="Rosicrucian" class="mw-redirect">Rosicrucian</a> point of view)</li>
<li><a href="/w/index.php?title=Rev._Richard_Benson&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Rev. Richard Benson (page does not exist)">Benson, Richard</a>, <i>(<a href="http://www.the-tidings.com/2006/0825/benson.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.the-tidings.com/2006/0825/benson.htm" rel="nofollow">The Just War Theory: A traditional Catholic moral view</a>)</i>, The Tidings (2006). (Showing the <a href="/wiki/Catholic" title="Catholic">Catholic</a> view in three points, including <a href="/wiki/John_Paul_II" title="John Paul II" class="mw-redirect">John Paul II</a>'s position concerning war)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Michael_Walzer" title="Michael Walzer">Michael Walzer</a> <i>Just and Unjust Wars: A Moral Argument with Historical Illustrations</i>, 4th ed., (New York: Basic Books, 1977). <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0465037070" class="internal">ISBN 0-465-03707-0</a>.</li>
<li>Uwe Steinhoff, <i>On the Ethics of War and Terrorism</i> (Oxford, Oxford University Press, 2007). Covers the basics and some of the most controversial current debates.</li>
<li>David Roberts MacDonald, <i>Padre E. C. Crosse and 'the Devonshire Epitaph': The Astonishing Story of One Man at the Battle of the Somme (with Antecedents to Today's 'Just War' Dialogue)</i>, 2007 <a href="/wiki/Cloverdale_Books" title="Cloverdale Books" class="mw-redirect">Cloverdale Books</a>, South Bend. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781929569458" class="internal">ISBN 978-1-929569-45-8</a></li>
<li>Irfan Khawaja, Review of Larry May, <i>War Crimes and Just War</i>, in <i><a href="/wiki/Democratiya" title="Democratiya">Democratiya</a></i> 10, (<a href="http://www.democratiya.com/review.asp?reviews_id=124" class="external autonumber" title="http://www.democratiya.com/review.asp?reviews_id=124" rel="nofollow">[1]</a>), an extended critique of just war theory.</li>
</ul>
<p>Michael W. Brough, John W. Lango, Harry van der Linden, eds., <i>Rethinking the Just War Tradition</i> (Albany, NY: SUNY Press, 2007). Discusses the contemporary relevance of just war theory. Offers an annotated bibliography of current writings on just war theory.</p>
<ul>
<li>v. Starck, Christian (Hrsg.): Kann es heute noch gerechte Kriege geben?, Wallstein-Verlag 2008</li>
</ul>
